name: Makan
review_text:
First impression, comfy looking decor, menu looks good. Staff are nice.
Food arrive, nice entrees but they are sweet? Maybe just the entree
Main arrives, confusion hits. Why is everything sweet?????
Lamb very fatty cuts, deep fried and douched in this sweet syrup. Couldn’t eat it after 2 bites. The chicken, crispy texture on the outside but flavourless, doesn’t taste like anything. Sat there chewing on this poached chicken like interior.
Really twisted my arm to buy their $9 sambal, which was also mid.
I have been to Indonesia and this is the furtherest from it. Close to Filipino food if anything  (given everything is sweet). It’s fine to do whatever fusion you did here but just don't call it Indonesian food.
High expectations but didn’t live up to it.

name: Makan
review_text:
My first time to try Indonesian dishes, and it was an interesting experience. We ordered a variety of dishes, including Gohu, Urutan, Jagung Bakar, Ayam Bakar Betutu, Rendang Sapi, Tahu Sambal Ijo, and Nasi Putih.
The atmosphere was great—relaxed and vibrant, which added to the dining experience. As for the food, I found some dishes a bit too spicy and oily for my taste, but my Indonesian colleagues absolutely loved everything. They were particularly fond of the rich flavors and the variety of textures in the dishes, which gave me a good insight into authentic Indonesian cuisine.
Overall, it’s a good spot to explore Indonesian flavors, especially if you enjoy bold, spicy dishes. While it wasn’t quite to my taste, I can see why it’s a hit with those who love this style of food. Definitely worth a visit if you’re curious about Indonesian cuisine.

name: Makan
review_text:
Overall, alright for a brush with Indonesian food. I feel the food is more fusion than authentic Indonesian (for context I’m Indonesian). But it’s still a great spot if you’re curious to try Indonesian food, but intimidated by the spices.
I think our favourite and a must get menu were the lamb ribs. They were absolutely tender and juicy, but their marinade is on the sweeter side. I loved it, though.
Their nasi goreng was also seasoned on the sweeter side. But we ordered their sambal terasi to accompany with the nasi goreng and it went perfect. They definitely nailed the spiciness of the sambal terasi, but I wished they added more terasi.
Pork slider was mediocre. I couldn’t really taste the seasoning. The buns were tender and lovely, though. On the other hand, I enjoyed the soft-shell crab buns more. It didn’t really taste “Indonesian”, but it was alright.
The caramelized pineapple tart was absolutely stellar. Loved how it’s reminiscent of nastar. Not a huge fan of the clove ice cream, though. I wished they had a tangier and fresher option, such as lime.
Check it out if you want to try some good lamb ribs.

name: Makan
review_text:
Had a fantastic dining experience at Makan, where I was served by Fabio, who truly made the evening memorable. Fabio was incredibly friendly, welcoming, and attentive – he made us feel right at home and added such a warm touch to our meal. His excellent service really stood out!
As for the food, here’s my take based on an Indonesian palate:
1. Kerupuk - 10/10
Perfectly done! The kerupuk tasted authentic, just like back home, and the warm peanut sauce was spot-on – the temperature was ideal and made each bite so enjoyable.
2. Kepiting Saos Padang - 7/10
I was hoping for a bit more of that rich, savory kick you get with Saos Padang, with seafood egg and spiciness coming through strongly. This was a bit on the sweet chili side, but it was still tasty, especially with the bun served warm.
3. Gohu - 10/10
Without a doubt, the best tuna tartare I’ve had! The spices really packed a punch, giving it that Indonesian sambal taste. Even though the sambal’s texture was creamy, it worked perfectly with the soft, creamy tuna flavor. A must-try!
4. Ayam Goreng Kecap - 8/10
Great crunch and texture! The sweet soy was rich, maybe a bit too sweet, which masked some of the chicken’s umami flavor. I think it would be even better paired with rice.
5. Rendang, Semur Tahu, and Nasi Serai - 10/10
This combo was a taste of home! The rendang was soft with a slightly more watery consistency, just like the homemade rendang you get in Indonesia – comforting and flavorful. The nasi was fragrant without overpowering the rendang spices, and the semur tahu added a nice balance, subtly seasoned and paired perfectly with the rendang.
Overall, Makan is a highly recommended place to eat, especially if you’re craving some authentic Indonesian flavors. I'll definitely be coming back.

name: Makan
review_text:
makan is an indonesian restaurant in the heart of the cbd. run by sisters tasia & gracia seger who originally ran pop ups and private dinners, they’ve translated their home-style cooking into a commercial context.
the word makan in indonesian simply means eat. and eat we did!
after starting with a deliciously sweet (and deceivingly strong) lechi martini and spicy elderflower martini we were spoilt with starters. the gohu (red curry tuna tartare) had the perfect ccocnutty heat, addictive with cassava crackers, and their sate maranggi (beef skewers) were tender and generously coated in a sweet soy shallot marinade. our fav was the martabak, gracia explaining to us that the street food originates from areas of indonesia with middle eastern influence, hence the hint of cumin in this duck mince crepe. SO good you’ll be licking your fingers.
mains were just as aromatic. the nasi goreng was generous and deeper in wok hei than others I’ve tried. the iga kambing (lamb ribs) were a medley of sticky sweet, sour and savoury. bebek goreng (twice cooked duck) is impressively tender on its own but elevated with their range of increasingly hot sambals, our favourite being the mild, sweet sambal including red peppers. I probably wouldn’t have opted for two fried mains, but these were part of the chefs selection menu and we enjoyed nonetheless! the urap (snake beans and bean sprouts) were a tasty and refreshing side.
their cendol coconut panacotta was a delight to eat, not too sweet and hunting for the pandan jelly. their cinnamon, crispy filo was also lovely and paired well with the ginger cream and spicy poached pear beneath.
at makan you can feel, see and taste the love in the dishes. the sisters run all dishes by their mum before adding them to the menu for that authentic indonesian tick of approval!
thank you for hosting us, we felt so welcome!

name: Makan
review_text: Food was average with slightly burnt Beef Rendang probably from reheating. It’s only when I was paying the bills that I received a rudely staff who whispered to her colleague next to her about me. She’s of a minority group herself and I was shocked to find her gossiping about me, her customer, even before me leaving the restaurant. I wanted to confront her but decided to walk away feeling gobsmacked. Apparently from other reviewers, services from this restaurant is an issue and I can personally see why.
owner_answer:
Dear Janice, 
Thank you for taking the time to inform us about your experience at Makan, and we would like to apologise for your experience with us.
We have informed the kitchen about the quality of the Beef Rendang you received that day, and will continue to work on improving and maintaining our standards.
Regarding the behaviour of our staff, please rest assured that we take matters like this very seriously, and will conduct internal checks with our staff to ensure such behaviour is not repeated.
Once again, we would like to thank you for bringing this matter to our attention, and invite you to reach out to us via email at makan@makaninmelbourne.com.au if you have any further feedback that you would like to discuss with us.
Sincerely,
Makan Restaurant.
